vice.isValid)\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:209:    @Published var email = \"\"\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:212:        !email.isEmpty && password.count >= 8\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:221:    @StateObject private var authService = AuthService()\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:225:            TextField(\"Email\", text: $authService.email)\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:226:            SecureField(\"Password\", text: $authService.password)\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:229:                    try? await authService.login()\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:232:            .disabled(!authService.isValid)\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:241:    @State private var email = \"\"\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:246:            TextField(\"Email\", text: $email)\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/layout-best-practices.md:250:                    if !email.isEmpty && password.count >= 8 {\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/latest-apis.md:351:    var email: String = \"\"\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/latest-apis.md:364:    @Published var email: String = \"\"\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:30:**CWE:** CWE-862 (Missing Authorization), CWE-639 (IDOR)\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:33:The function `get_conversation_with_stats` is declared as `SECURITY DEFINER`, which means it executes with the **privileges of the function owner** (typically the database superuser/postgres role), not the calling user. It accepts an arbitrary `conversation_uuid` parameter and returns conversation data **without any `auth.uid() = user_id` check**.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:49:Because `SECURITY DEFINER` runs as the function owner, the RLS policies on `conversations` and `messages` are **completely bypassed**. Any authenticated user who knows (or brute-forces) a conversation UUID can call this function via `supabaseClient.rpc(\"get_conversation_with_stats\", params: ...)` and retrieve another user's conversation title, persona name, message count, and last message timestamp.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:51:**Impact:** Full IDOR -- any authenticated user can enumerate and read metadata of any other user's conversations.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:54:Add an explicit `auth.uid()` check inside the function body:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:56:WHERE c.id = conversation_uuid AND c.user_id = auth.uid()\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:67:**CWE:** CWE-862 (Missing Authorization), CWE-639 (IDOR)\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:80:While this code is currently commented out (the Supabase repositories are not active), it is production-ready template code that will be uncommented when Supabase is enabled. The RLS policy on `messages` does enforce `auth.uid() = user_id`, which provides server-side protection. However, defense-in-depth requires the application layer to also filter by `user_id` to prevent accidental exposure if RLS is ever misconfigured or disabled during migration.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:97:The edge function sets `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: '*'`, allowing any origin to make authenticated cross-origin requests:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:102:  'Access-Control-Allow-Headers': 'authorization, x-client-info, apikey, content-type',\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:106:Since the `Authorization` header is in the allowed headers list, a malicious website can make cross-origin requests to this edge function using a user's JWT token (if obtained through XSS or token leakage). While mobile apps are not affected by CORS, if this edge function is also accessed via web clients, this is a direct vulnerability.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:108:**Impact:** Enables cross-origin abuse of the AI chat endpoint from any domain. Could be used for unauthorized AI API consumption or abuse if tokens are compromised.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:146:### MED-01: `cleanup_old_conversations` SECURITY DEFINER with `auth.uid()` Dependency\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:149:**CWE:** CWE-863 (Incorrect Authorization)\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:152:The `cleanup_old_conversations` function is `SECURITY DEFINER` but correctly includes `AND user_id = auth.uid()` in its WHERE clause. However, `SECURITY DEFINER` functions run as the function owner, which means:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:153:1. If called from a context where `auth.uid()` is NULL (e.g., service role, cron job, or direct database connection), the `auth.uid()` check returns NULL and the DELETE matches zero rows (safe due to NULL comparison semantics).\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:159:Change to `SECURITY INVOKER` so RLS policies apply naturally, or remove `SECURITY DEFINER` and let the standard RLS DELETE policy handle authorization.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:166:**CWE:** CWE-939 (Improper Authorization in Handler for Custom URL Scheme)\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:214:The `DeviceTokenUploader` constructs an `HTTPRequest` without setting an `Authorization` header. It relies on the `httpClient` having an `AuthInterceptor` attached. From the `CompositionRoot` (line 258 of AppDelegate), the uploader reuses `environment.compositionRoot.httpClient`, which does have `AuthInterceptor` configured.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:216:However, the `DeviceTokenUploader` itself has no knowledge of or dependency on authentication. If it is ever instantiated with a plain `HTTPClient` without the interceptor (e.g., in a different composition context or test), the device token would be uploaded without authentication, allowing unauthenticated token registration.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:220:**Impact:** Depends entirely on backend validation. If the backend `/v1/device/register` endpoint does not require auth, arbitrary token registration is possible.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:223:1. Add explicit `Authorization` header in `DeviceTokenUploader` or document the auth requirement in the API contract.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:224:2. Ensure the backend endpoint validates the JWT and associates the token with the authenticated user.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:233:**CWE:** CWE-862 (Missing Authorization)\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:280:| Edge Function (`ai/index.ts`) | YES | `supabaseClient.auth.getUser()` validates JWT | Returns 401 on failure. Correct. |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:281:| DeviceTokenUploader | INDIRECT | Relies on `AuthInterceptor` in HTTP client pipeline | No standalone auth. See MED-04. |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:282:| Supabase RLS (conversations) | YES | `auth.uid() = user_id` on SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE | Complete coverage. Correct. |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:283:| Supabase RLS (messages) | YES | `auth.uid() = user_id` on SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE | Complete coverage. Correct. |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:284:| `get_conversation_with_stats` | **NO** | `SECURITY DEFINER` bypasses RLS, no `auth.uid()` check | **CRIT-01** |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:285:| `cleanup_old_conversations` | YES (fragile) | `SECURITY DEFINER` with `auth.uid()` in WHERE clause | See MED-01. |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:286:| Local SwiftData repos | N/A | Single-user local DB, no auth needed | See LOW-01. |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:296:| `cleanup_old_conversations` | No | `user_id = auth.uid()` in function body | Scoped to own data |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:310:1. **[CRITICAL]** Add `AND c.user_id = auth.uid()` to `get_conversation_with_stats` or change to `SECURITY INVOKER`.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/missingauth-results.md:317:8. **[MEDIUM]** Add explicit auth requirement documentation/enforcement to `DeviceTokenUploader`.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:41:  - OpenRouter API key fragments if an auth error occurs during the `fetch()` call\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:139:      'Access-Control-Allow-Headers': 'authorization, x-client-info, apikey, content-type',\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:142:- **Risk:** The wildcard CORS origin allows any website to make authenticated requests to this edge function. While the function does verify Supabase auth tokens, if a user has an active Supabase session in their browser:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:146:- **Mitigating Factor:** The function requires an `Authorization` header with a valid Supabase JWT, which limits cookie-based CSRF. However, if the app has a web companion or if tokens are stored in localStorage, this becomes exploitable.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:195:  - `get_conversation_with_stats`: Takes a UUID parameter and returns conversation data. Any authenticated user can query ANY conversation by UUID, because RLS is bypassed.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:196:  - `cleanup_old_conversations`: Correctly filters by `auth.uid()` inside the function body, which partially mitigates the RLS bypass.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:197:- **Impact:** `get_conversation_with_stats` is an **IDOR vulnerability** -- any authenticated user can read any other user's conversation metadata (title, persona_name, message count, timestamps) by guessing or enumerating UUIDs.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:198:- **Remediation:** Add `auth.uid()` filtering inside the SECURITY DEFINER function, or change to `SECURITY INVOKER`:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:201:  WHERE c.id = conversation_uuid AND c.user_id = auth.uid()\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:279:- **Keychain** for tokens (secure enclave, no file paths)\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:289:2. **Supabase Auth:** JWT-based auth with token refresh; tokens stored in Keychain\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/injection-results.md:290:3. **Row Level Security:** All tables have RLS policies filtering by `auth.uid()`\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/animation-basics.md:259:            print(\"Animation: \\(newValue)\")\napps/waketask-iphone/.agents/skills/swiftui-expert-skill/references/animation-advanced.md:277:print(midpoint.scale)  // Value at 0.25 seconds\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:42:### Finding 3: Bearer Token Fragments in Test File\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:47:  let token = \"Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9\"\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:59:  let apiKey = \"sk-1234567890abcdef\"\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:61:- **Risk**: None. This is a fabricated test value used to verify the `AppLogger.redacted()` function correctly masks strings matching the `sk-` pattern.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:71:  static let SUPABASE_URL = \"https://placeholder.supabase.co\"\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:72:  static let SUPABASE_ANON_KEY = \"placeholder-key-for-debug-mode\"\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:73:  static let REVENUECAT_API_KEY = \"placeholder_rc_key\"\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:101:  _ = try await manager.signUpWithEmail(email: \"test@example.com\", password: \"password123\")\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:102:  _ = try await manager.signInWithEmail(email: \"wrong@example.com\", password: \"wrong\")\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:104:- **Risk**: None. These are test-only passwords used with a `MockAuthClient` in unit tests. No connection to any real backend occurs. The email addresses (`test@example.com`) are also clearly fabricated.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:116:- **Risk**: The wildcard CORS policy allows any origin to call the AI proxy edge function. While the function requires authentication (JWT verification via `supabaseClient.auth.getUser()`), the open CORS could facilitate token-replay attacks from malicious websites if a user's JWT is compromised. This is a common pattern for mobile-first APIs but warrants review.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:129:- **Risk**: `SECURITY DEFINER` functions execute with the privileges of the function owner (typically the database superuser), not the calling user. If there is a SQL injection vulnerability in the function body, it could escalate privileges. In this case, both functions use parameterized queries and include `auth.uid()` checks, reducing risk. However, `get_conversation_with_stats` does NOT filter by `auth.uid()`, meaning any authenticated user could query stats for any conversation UUID.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:130:- **Remediation**: Add `WHERE c.user_id = auth.uid()` to `get_conversation_with_stats` to enforce row-level authorization within the function. Consider changing to `SECURITY INVOKER` if RLS policies should apply.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:139:  SUPABASE_URL = https://...\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:140:  SUPABASE_ANON_KEY = ...\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:141:  REVENUECAT_API_KEY = ...\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:174:- **Risk**: MEDIUM. These placeholders are guarded by `#if DEBUG` and an environment variable check, so they will not appear in release builds. However, in debug builds with `AUTH_BYPASS=1`, the app connects to `https://placeholder.supabase.co` with a fake key. If someone registers `placeholder.supabase.co`, they could potentially intercept debug auth requests. More practically, this is a development convenience pattern that is safe if developers understand it.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:184:  REVENUECAT_API_KEY = appl_YOUR_KEY\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:185:  SUPABASE_ANON_KEY = eyJ...YOUR_ANON_KEY...\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:186:  supabase secrets set OPENROUTER_API_KEY=sk-or-v1-YOUR_KEY_HERE\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:200:4. **AppLogger.redacted()** - Comprehensive PII/secret redaction in logging (tested for `sk-`, `pk-`, Bearer tokens, JWTs).\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:203:7. **Edge Function uses environment variables** - `Deno.env.get('OPENROUTER_API_KEY')` keeps the OpenRouter key server-side only.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:205:9. **JWT verification in Edge Function** - `supabaseClient.auth.getUser()` validates tokens before processing requests.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/hardcodedsecrets-results.md:217:| **P2** | Add `auth.uid()` check to `get_conversation_with_stats` SQL function | #9 |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:22:The audit identified **4 critical vulnerabilities** that require immediate attention. The most severe is a **complete paywall bypass** (BL-001) where the free tier message limit is dead code. Combined with **no server-side enforcement** on the AI edge function, any authenticated user has unlimited, unmetered access to the AI API. The third critical finding is an **IDOR in a SECURITY DEFINER function** that leaks any user's conversation metadata. The fourth is **error message information disclosure** in the edge function.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:24:**Positive findings:** The codebase demonstrates strong security fundamentals -- Keychain token storage, PII redaction in logs, RLS on all database tables, no hardcoded secrets in committed code, proxy architecture keeping API keys server-side, and type-safe deserialization throughout.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:63:The Supabase Edge Function only validates auth (JWT), then proxies directly to OpenRouter with:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:70:**Any authenticated user can `curl` the endpoint directly and consume unlimited AI API credits.**\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:96:| **CWE** | CWE-639 (IDOR), CWE-862 (Missing Authorization) |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:99:The `get_conversation_with_stats` function is `SECURITY DEFINER` (bypasses RLS) and has **no `auth.uid()` filter**. Any authenticated user can call `supabaseClient.rpc(\"get_conversation_with_stats\", { conversation_uuid: \"...\" })` with any UUID and retrieve another user's conversation title, persona name, message count, and timestamps.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:103:WHERE c.id = conversation_uuid AND c.user_id = auth.uid()\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:178:| 16 | MED-04 | DeviceTokenUploader has no standalone auth dependency | DeviceTokenUploader.swift |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:191:| 22 | LOW-01 | Local SwiftData repos have no auth checks | ConversationRepositoryImpl.swift |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:204:| P3 | Auth tokens stored in iOS Keychain | Proper use of `SecureStore` for access/refresh tokens |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:205:| P4 | RLS enabled on all database tables | Proper `auth.uid() = user_id` policies on SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:207:| P6 | PII redaction in logging | `AppLogger.redacted()` masks JWT, Bearer tokens, API keys |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:210:| P9 | Debug mock auth gated by `#if DEBUG` | Compile-time guard, not present in release builds |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:221:| **P0 (Today)** | CRIT-01: Add auth.uid() to get_conversation_with_stats | 10 min | Fixes IDOR |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/final-report.md:244:| `sast/missingauth-results.md` | Missing auth & IDOR scan (11 findings) |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:6:**Scope:** Paywall bypass, race conditions, auth bypass, subscription validation, edge function security\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:58:- The function only checks `auth.getUser()` for authentication, then immediately proxies to OpenRouter\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:60:A user with a valid auth token can call the edge function directly (e.g., via `curl`) and bypass the client-side limit entirely. The `messages` array in the request body is forwarded directly to OpenRouter without any size validation.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:62:**Impact:** Any authenticated user can consume unlimited AI API credits by calling the edge function directly, completely circumventing the paywall.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:86:An authenticated user can specify any model available on OpenRouter, including expensive ones like `anthropic/claude-opus-4-0-20250514` or `openai/gpt-4-32k`, leading to dramatically higher API costs.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:108:The edge function has no rate limiting mechanism. An authenticated user can send unlimited requests in rapid succession. There is no:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:194:The edge function only checks Supabase auth -- it has zero awareness of subscription status.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:269:The edge function allows requests from any origin. While the auth token requirement mitigates unauthorized access, the wildcard CORS policy means any website can make authenticated requests if it obtains a user's token (e.g., via XSS on another domain).\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:285:The mock auth bypass uses Swift's compile-time `#if DEBUG` directive:\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:289:let authBypassValue = ProcessInfo.processInfo.environment[\"AUTH_BYPASS\"]\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:290:let shouldUseMock = authBypassValue != \"0\"\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:296:This is a **compile-time** check. In RELEASE builds, the `shouldUseMock` variable is hard-coded to `false` and the mock auth code is stripped by the compiler. The `AUTH_BYPASS` environment variable cannot affect production builds.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/businesslogic-results.md:346:This code reads custom headers from environment variables without a `#if DEBUG` guard. In theory, on a jailbroken device, an attacker could inject custom headers into LLM proxy requests. However, the practical risk is low since the AuthInterceptor adds the Bearer token separately and takes precedence.\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/architecture.md:10:| Auth mechanism | Supabase GoTrue (Apple Sign In, Google Sign In, Email/Password), Keychain token storage |\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/architecture.md:22:- **Auth**: Supabase GoTrue authentication (Apple, Google, Email), session/token management via Keychain\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/architecture.md:24:- **Storage**: SwiftData persistence for conversations/messages/settings, Keychain for secrets\napps/waketask-iphone/sast/architecture.md:34